<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How 'green' are the oil giants? That is the question investigated in Channel
4's Critical Eye: The Heat of the Moment (9.00). Oil discoveries have never
done a lot of good for the environment. Filmed secretly in Ecuador,
Nigerian, Gabon and Papua and New Guinea, the film suggests that despite the
much flaunted green credentials of oil companies, drilling means health
risks for the locals and irreparable damage to disappearing habitats.
If you are looking for something which will weigh less heavy on the soul,
tonight is strong on comedy although of the four on offer only the geriatric
jollities on BBC 1's Waiting For God (8.30) is actually new.
Choucroute has always seemed to me as one of the more horrible dishes of
French cuisine - although it can always be blamed on the Germans. However,
there are many more palatable aspects of Alsatian cooking as Mireille
Johnston amply demonstrates in A Cook's Tour of France: Alsace on BBC 2
(8.00). Ghouls have a feast with Crimewatch File: Murder Without Motive on
BBC1 at 9.30, re-enacting an appalling murder solved with the help of
psychologists and handwriting experts.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
