<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / CBI sees little risk of pay spiral
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DANGER of a price-wage spiral developing as a result of Britain's
withdrawal from the exchange rate mechanism is 'limited' given the present
weak state of the labour market, according to the Confederation of British
Industry.
The latest CBI pay and performance analysis for 1992-93 warns, however, that
if 'employers do not keep a firm grip on pay and continue to improve
performance, the benefits (of ERM withdrawal) will be squandered through
higher inflation'.
Over the past year UK earnings growth has finally fallen below the EC
average. But the CBI points out that the EC figure has been inflated by high
increases in Germany which will not last and that the UK is still well above
US and Japanese levels. In the three years to 1991 unit labour cost
increases in the UK were higher than in the US and Japan and higher than the
European average. This year the UK has done better, 'but not well enough to
regain lost ground'. The CBI argues that employees have become much more
realistic about pay, with survey evidence showing that 65 per cent of
employees expect their next pay increase to be the same or lower than last
year. Two thirds of employers now have performance pay for some or all of
their white-collar staff while one in four has it for manual workers.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, repeats his plea for a freeze on the
overall pay bill in the public sector. But the CBI itself estimates that the
1992-93 pay rise for nurses is likely to be 5.7 per cent, the armed forces
more than 5 per cent and teachers 7.5 per cent. Manufacturing pay increases
remain around 4 per cent. Since 1979 white-collar average earnings have
risen 38 per cent compared with 11 per cent for blue-collar staff. That has
prompted the CBI to ask members to take a closer look at white-collar pay
and push for more 'multi-skilling' for such workers.
In terms of output per worker, UK manufacturers moved closer to German
competitors in the late 1980s but there has been some slippage since the
recession began.
The CBI now estimates that absence from work is costing British business
Pounds 7.5bn a year - equivalent to 3 per cent of the pay bill.
Pay and Performance 1992-93. CBI, Centre Point, London WC1A 1DU.
</TEXT>
