<TEXT>
CAMPAIGNERS for the reten-tion of the wages councils yesterday stepped up
their efforts on the eve of the Tory conference speech by Mrs Gillian
Shephard, the employment secretary, David Goodhart writes.
Mrs Shephard is not expected to announce the abolition of the councils -
which set minimum pay rates for nearly 10 per cent of the workforce - in
today's speech, but campaigners against abolition are convinced, as a result
of recent correspondence with her, that she will include abolition in this
autumn's employment bill.
Ms Mo Mowlam, shadow minister for women, published a report arguing that
wages councils had been an important force for pay equality.
Mrs Shephard has written to the Equal Opportunities Commission pointing out
there was a clear body of research demonstrating 'the relationship between
higher pay and fewer jobs'.
