<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Japan seen to be victim of bias by newspapers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COVERAGE of Japan in many British national newspapers is negative and biased
with a heavy concentration on whale hunting, war atrocity and 'funny Jap'
stories, according to a new study.
The survey - by Professor Douglas Anthony, professor of Japanese studies at
Cardiff University, and sponsored by Andersen Consulting - was based on a
study of the national and regional press from January to June 1991. Each
article was rated as positive, neutral or negative.
The mass-market tabloids, with the exception of the Daily Mirror, use
'viciousness, vacuity and sheer negative spitefulness in their treatment of
items on Japan', the report argues. However, Today and the Daily Mail both
had more neutral than negative stories.
Coverage in the broadsheet papers was much greater but still less than
Japan's size or importance merited.
The Financial Times had the most articles on Japan - 639. After that came
The Independent with 188 and The Times with 180. Such a high proportion of
the FT's coverage was judged to be neutral that it was not considered worth
making a full breakdown.
The Sunday broadsheets, apart from their financial pages, were largely
negative.
</TEXT>
