FT  08 OCT 92 / Accountants to probe Church
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COOPERS &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm, has been appointed to report on the
finances of the Church of England following criticism of the Church
Commissioners' investment performance.
The church asked Coopers to examine 'the commissioners' borrowings and the
information flow required for the management of their assets'.
Dr George Carey, who as archbishop of Canterbury is chairman of the
commissioners, promised the Church's general synod in July that there would
be an inquiry. He said 'serious points' had been made about the management
of funds and about judgments on investments.
The undertaking followed an article in the Financial Times in July which
said the commissioners, who are responsible for handling the church's main
assets, had suffered Pounds 500m losses on investments.
In their annual report for last year, the commissioners said that they
expected annual income to remain flat for some years and that it had 'become
urgent' to cut expenditure to match income forecasts.
One of the consequences is that church members have been told they will have
to meet a higher proportion of clergy stipends in future.
In the synod debate Sir Douglas Lovelock, first church estates commissioner
and chairman of the assets committee, defended the commissioners. He said
there was not an institution in the country whose capital value had not gone
down in the past year or two.
