<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Smooth ride for the 'bus
candidate'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT takes the chutzpah of Mr Kenneth Clarke to boast of making a flat speech
to conference. But then it is the home secretary's easy confidence that is
proving one of the more interesting sideshows of the week in Brighton.
In a post-speech briefing yesterday he complimented the delegates for their
'more mature' attitude to the law and order debate - in the past a ritual
demonstration of Tory bloodlust.
'It was a serious and perfectly sensible debate and I'm glad about that,' he
said. 'It is the first time as far as I know that not a sole member of the
audience mentioned hanging or flogging - the Birmingham Six case has had its
effect.'
That frank appraisal came with the observation that law and order probably
was a more relevant issue to the public than all the Conservatives' public
hand-wringing about the Maastricht treaty.
Such calming sentiments are just one reason why Mr Clarke is increasingly
seen as the 'bus candidate' for the leadership - the man most likely to
succeed should Mr John Major disappear under a double-decker.
All week, indeed, all last week as well, it has been the ever-relaxed,
affably-voiced, suede-shoed home secretary who has appeared before the
cameras to bat aside the increasingly vituperative rhetoric of the
anti-Maastricht legions. He incurred their wrath on Tuesday by acknowledging
that he had not read the treaty and opining that probably few of his cabinet
colleagues had done so either.
While provoking paroxysms from the rebels, this very human - not to say
unpolitical - admission clearly appeals to the large element in the party
for whom life-and-death issues are both wearying and slightly improbable.
Yesterday, a similar, anti-hysterical tone pervaded Mr Clarke's law and
order speech. Britain was not any more lawless a country than its
neighbours, indeed, perhaps less so.
But he had identified a specific group of juvenile delinquent offenders who
were at the root of a huge quantity of crime. It was no good for them and no
good for us, he pragmatically observed, so he would do something about it.
Later, Mr Clarke was at it again, casually dismissing the imminent arrival
of Lady Thatcher as an amusing but rather irrelevant sideshow. 'We always
used to have our dust-ups in this great movement of ours,' he observed. 'It
was only Margaret who shut them down. What is new now is that we also have
the battle of the biographies.'
Cornered for a few remarks on his former employer, Mr Clarke happily
volunteered that he though it a bit rich that the woman who had brought
Britain into the exchange rate mechanism was now attacking it.
'Margaret saying 'I didn't mean to do it, I was bullied'' amounted to
'denying the history of her premiership', he said, laughing at the image of
Mr Major twisting the prime ministerial arm behind her back.
On the treaty itself, he merely observed: 'We will get it through . . with
difficulty.'
To some, the Clarke style of infinite reasonableness is irritating. But to
many others in what, after all, has often been called the non-political
party, it makes a refreshing change from the destructive ideological warfare
that the Thatcher epoch left in its wake.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-14797</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJHBUAB7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921008
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Curtain up on a
guerrilla war - Conference Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORGET Maastricht. It is the economy that counts.
For those with their eyes on Brighton, that will require a certain amount of
self-discipline. Lord Tebbit offered a vivid reminder this week that the
Tory party has still to catch up with Britain's distinctly modest place in
the world.
Lady Thatcher, who will join Mr John Major in a cruelly synthetic show of
solidarity on the Brighton platform this morning, will not be silenced. Her
unbridled assault on the exchange rate mechanism and on Maastricht in
today's issue of The European is nothing less than a direct attack on the
leadership of her successor.
It took more than two decades for the Conservatives to come grudgingly to
terms with the end of empire.
It is taking them longer still to realise that it is Britain rather than
Europe which is left isolated when fog descends upon the Channel.
So the emotional outpouring on the conference floor triggered by a cynically
brilliant speech from Essex Man (to be followed we can be sure by a similar
reception for Grantham Woman) foreshadows months of guerrilla warfare at
Westminster.
There will be a debate in principle on the legislation during the second
week after MPs return to the Commons on October 19. But senior ministers
have yet to decide whether Mr John Major can risk bringing the committee
stage forward before the Edinburgh summit.
Once detailed examination of the bill starts it will have to be taken 'on
the run', with all other legislative business pushed to one side for three
or four weeks. But during Britain's EC presidency, up to 10 ministers will
be abroad on any one day.
The prime minister has been told that his parliamentary business managers
can guarantee majorities against the wrecking tactics of the Tory
Euro-sceptics only if those ministers drop their presidency duties to stay
at Westminster.
So the committee stage might yet be deferred until the new year, leaving the
divisions to fester throughout the autumn. Royal Assent may in the end rely
on Labour abstentions.
But the important point is that no one - Lord Tebbit no more than Mr Douglas
Hurd - doubts that the government has the capacity to ratify Maastricht. At
the end of the day Conservative heads will rule Tory hearts.
The economy offers no such certainty.
Those expecting Mr Norman Lamont to conjure from a magic box a blueprint for
a totally new economic policy will be disappointed. Life outside the ERM is
not that simple.
The chancellor will set out the parameters of a strategy, which will be
familiar to anyone who watched the then Mr Nigel Lawson struggle to frame
his policy during the mid 1980s.
The starting point is that the objective of consistently low inflation has
not changed. The delivery mechanism will be tight control of public spending
 -if it can, the Treasury will undershoot its Pounds 244.5bn target for next
year - and a mix of monetary indicators to determine interest rates.
The value of the pound will, as Mr Lawson used to say, be 'taken into
account'. Sticking to the public spending targets, which are much tougher in
the two succeeding years than in 1993-94, should allow modest reductions in
income tax in the approach to the next election.
There will be a confirmation that house prices are to join MO and M3 in the
Treasury's list of monetary indicators. But the chancellor will not risk
sending his audience to sleep with a detailed tour around the motorways of
the money supply. Nigel Lawson tried that once in the early 1980s. It left
his audience glued to their seats.
Mr Lamont's first priority is to demonstrate that he still deserves to
retain the keys to No 11 Downing Street - first to his audience in Brighton
and through their acclaim to the financial markets. But for many colleagues
his speech - and the more detailed exposition which will follow at the House
of Commons next week - will be no more than a staging post. They want
sterling back in the ERM - not this month or next but within perhaps a year.
One of the most striking things this week has been how the conference has
reinforced the natural authority of the troika of enthusiastic Europeans at
the top of the cabinet.
Mr Hurd saw off the Euro-sceptics in a brilliant speech. Mr Michael
Heseltine did likewise in typically more flamboyant style. Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the heir apparent if Mr Major were to suffer a nasty traffic
accident, has added a layer of prime ministerial gravitas to his robust
political style.
These ministers have not been singing in their baths. Instead they have
given every sign that they are concerned that the pound may go into free
fall.
They see no reason to fight the ERM battle now. They acknowledge the
difficulties posed by Maastricht. They also see the economic case for
caution about the timing of re-entry.
Next spring or summer seems a more realistic bet. So for the moment Messrs
Hurd Heseltine and Clarke echo Mr Lamont's formula that sterling will float
for the 'foreseeable future'. But the ghost of the ERM has not been banished
from the cabinet table.
</TEXT>
