<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party at Brighton: Ministers unite to back
Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT and Mr Michael Heseltine joined forces yesterday in
vigorous defences of the Maastricht agreement, as ministers on all sides of
the argument proclaimed the treaty's virtues in conference proceedings again
dominated by Europe.
The chancellor of the exchequer and the trade and industry secretary
insisted the treaty was a victory for Britain and a turning-point in pushing
back the tide of European centralisation and the danger of federalism.
Reminding his audience of the concessions made by other EC countries during
the negotiations, Mr Lamont emphasised that the treaty not only included
'subsidiarity' or minimum interference in the work of national governments
by the European Commission, but also spelt out the areas which should be
dealt with through co-operation between governments, such as home and
foreign affairs.
In a wide-ranging speech to the Conservative Political Centre on the future
of Europe, the chancellor said the EC should be a 'community of nations' not
a 'superstate'. While there was widespread support for defending Britain's
independence in Europe, he saw no similar legitimacy for a European
government.
'At present I do not believe that there is a European identity of anything
like the quality and strength of the several national identities that exist
within the Community,' he said, though he warned that perpetual vigilance
was needed against the Community's tendency to centralise.
He admitted that, with the extension of qualified majority voting to
single-market issues under the single European act, some British sovereignty
had been ceded, but said that those restrictions were 'as nothing' set
against the benefits of the single market.
Nonetheless, there had to be a clear limit on what was suitable for
Community action. 'The main decisions concerning economic and fiscal policy
 -in particular taxation and government spending - must remain the
responsibilities of member states,' he said.
While dutifully adhering to the agreed cabinet position, he attacked
'petty-minded orders' that made the Commission a laughing stock. 'Those
things for which we want Europe to work together - such as free trade, fair
competition and prosperity - can be achieved by nation states within a
community . . and do not require the creation of a superstate,' he said.
It was 'totally inconsistent' for the Commission to call for more funding
from member states 'while at the same time preaching about the need to
reduce budget deficits.'
Earlier, in the main conference hall, Mr Heseltine faced down some rowdy
Euro-sceptic interventions in a performance that won him a standing ovation
during his speech as well as at its end.
He insisted that Mr John Major had gone to Maastricht 'to fight for our
essential interests'.
'And lost]' came a shout from the floor.
Mr Heseltine argued passionately that 'national self-interest' was the only
convincing reason for membership of the EC, and warned that if Britain were
left on the periphery of Europe, the future of the City of London and the
stream of inward investment from Japan and America would be at risk.
Mr Peter Lilley, a cabinet Euro-sceptic, said: 'We British have governed
ourselves for 1,000 years. Our laws, institutions and sovereign parliament
are the essence of our nationhood. And nationhood is the precondition of
democracy. That nationhood will not be extinguished. We won't let federalism
erode it away. We won't let Brussels take it away.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
