<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Lilley signals financial curbs on social security
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CLEAR signal that the social security department will become a casualty of
fierce Treasury curbs on public spending, which might yet see it reneging on
Conservative manifesto commitments, was given yesterday by Mr Peter Lilley,
social security secretary.
To escape the recession, 'we must curb public spending, including social
security', Mr Lilley told the Conservative conference.
Talking later to journalists, he refused even to reaffirm the Tories
election pledge to uprate child benefit in line with inflation, or discuss
possible hikes in the National Insurance contributions ceiling. 'I'm not
going to respond to specific items,' he insisted.
Mr Lilley is understood to be fighting the Treasury hard to avoid
overturning election promises, but a number of other cuts are fast becoming
probabilities.
These include reducing the period during which the jobless are entitled to
unemployment benefit from 12 months to six, although resulting savings would
be offset partially by higher Income Support payments. Housing benefit and
disability allowances could also be hit.
With discussions still continuing, the Treasury may still succeed in
imposing stronger control over the social security department's Pounds 70bn
budget. Legislation to end the statutory uprating of state pensions - which
will be based on September's inflation figure released tomorrow - is being
actively canvassed by the Treasury.
In a speech geared largely at playing to the instincts of many of the Tory
representatives, Mr Lilley promised renewed efforts to clamp down on social
security fraud, setting a target of Pounds 500m in savings this year and
hinting at a higher target for next year. 'I'm closing down the
something-for-nothing society,' he declared.
He singled out 'councillors who draw the dole to run leftwing campaigns' and
'young ladies who get pregnant just to jump the housing queue' as being on
his 'little list of benefit offenders who I'll soon be rooting out'.
Hinting that he is anxious to see greater targeting of benefits, Mr Lilley
said that 'improving benefits is not just a question of spending more money.
It's how we spend it that counts.'
But, while he wanted to focus benefits on the most needy, he wished also to
restore incentives to work which would limit the extent to which further
'means-testing' could be introduced. Other priorities included simplifying
the benefits system and encouraging personal responsibility. He stressed the
importance of absent parents contributing to the upkeep of their children.
He also announced the setting up of a new 'family credit' advice line.
Mr Lilley said the helpline would mean that, for the first time, a benefits
advice service would be available to potential claimants as well as those
already claiming family credit.
He also underlined his previous announcement of tougher rules affecting
so-called New Age Travellers.
</TEXT>
