FT  08 OCT 92 / UK is 'less attractive' destination for German waste: Paper
recycling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DECLINE of sterling has come as welcome news to at least one part of
British industry - the companies that collect and recycle waste paper.
The relative rise in the value of the D-Mark is expected to help staunch the
inflow of German material from recycled cardboard boxes which has been
playing havoc with the pricing structure of the UK market.
But Mr Peter Williams, chief executive of the David S. Smith paper and
packaging group, believes the pound's fall against other European currencies
is likely to bring only temporary respite to his industry.
'The devaluation has relieved some of the competitive pressures, making it
less attractive for continental Europeans to ship here,' he says. 'It will
help attenuate our problems, but it will not solve them.'
Spurred on by a big national recycling scheme, the German paper packaging
industry has benefited from an unlimited supply of cheap raw materials. But
surplus collected materials have moved out of Germany, driving down prices
across Europe and undermining the market economics of paper recycling
industries in other countries. 'The fundamental problem remains that many
continental European countries have state-driven mandated recycling systems
whereas we have a market-based system which is vulnerable to price
pressures,' Mr Williams says.
The Italian waste paper collection and recycling industries, which have been
similarly hit by the glut of German materials over the past year, are also
likely to experience some temporary relief following the lira's decline
against other currencies.
However, UK companies which buy recycled paper to convert into cardboard
boxes are likely to face increased cost pressures as a result of sterling's
decline.
</TEXT>
