FT  08 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Nafta treaty initialled in Texas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATION of the North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta) was formally
concluded in San Antonio, Texas, yesterday with a symbolic initialling by
Mrs Carla Hills, US trade representative, Mr Jaime Serra Puche, Mexico's
commerce secretary, and Mr Michael Wilson, Canada's trade and industry
minister, Our Foreign Staff reports.
They were flanked by the leaders of their respective countries. The
initialling must still be followed by formal signing and ratified by each
nation's legislatures. President Bush hopes the treaty will boost his
electoral chances, especially in states thought to gain from extra
US-Mexican trade, hence the choice of Texas for the initialling.
However the conditional support of Mr Bill Clinton, the Democratic
presidential candidate, for the treaty is likely to reduce, if not
eliminate, any such advantage.
An opinion poll by the Mexican Institute of Public Opinion showed 48 per
cent of Mexicans asked supported Nafta, down from previous estimates by
other organisations.
</TEXT>
