<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Public spending faces further cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT will today seek to restore the government's credibility in
financial markets by putting tough control of public spending at the heart
of the economic strategy which replaces UK membership of the European
exchange rate mechanism.
As the chancellor prepared to set out at the Tory conference the new ground
rules for his economic policy, cabinet colleagues said the Treasury wanted
to lower further the Pounds 244.5bn spending figure agreed for next year.
In spite of public admissions that the existing target would involve
significant cash reductions for most Whitehall spending programmes, the
minsters said the Treasury was emphasising that the figure was a 'ceiling'
rather than a target.
Ministers said the allocation of the overall budget between different
departments would not be agreed for several weeks, but it was already clear
several once-cherished projects would be cut.
The Treasury has told spending ministers that four unavoidable spending
increases - on the unemployed, EC farm subsidies, legal aid and on the
increased numbers in higher education - have more than wiped out the Pounds
4bn available from the Treasury's contingency reserve.
With more than Pounds 1bn allotted to ease the replacement of the poll tax
by the council tax, it would be impossible to avoid cash reductions in
budgets ranging from health to overseas aid.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, whose unemployment benefit
budget will rise sharply as a result of the recession, acknowledged
yesterday he faced much tighter constraints on discretion benefits for the
poor and disabled. Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, and Mr John
Patten, the education secretary, admitted they faced a squeeze on resources.
Mr Lamont intends to use his speech to the conference to set out the broad
parameters of his anti-inflation strategy.
Apart from tight control of spending, he will say interest rates will be set
to meet monetary targets with both exchange rate and asset prices taken into
account.
Business and sterling, Page 10
</TEXT>
