<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Russia faces ecological nightmare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN officials yesterday painted an apocalyptic picture of a country so
full of chemical and organic toxins that even if all pollution were
miraculously to stop today, the Russian people would be stunted for the next
quarter century.
'We have already doomed ourselves for the next 25 years,' Mr Vladimir
Pokrovsky, head of the Academy of Medical Sciences, told a news conference
called to publicise the Russian government's first full revelations of the
damage done to health and the environment by 70 years of communist rule.
The figures cited by Russia's top scientists and environmental politicians
were numbing. In a reversal unprecedented in industrialised countries, Mr
Pokrovsky predicted that diseases in pregnant women would rise from 83 in
1,000 to 110 in 1,000 in coming years.
Widespread ignorance of contraceptives, which are hard to obtain and used by
only one woman in five, resulted in 3.5m abortions at state hospitals last
year - 2.5 times more than the number of births.
Some 40 per cent of hospitals did not have hot water, while an additional 12
per cent had no water at all.
Russian infants fare no better after they are born, with 11 per cent of
infants suffering birth defects. They become more ill as they grow and about
55 per cent of schoolchildren suffer health problems.
Their health is worsened by the water they drink, half of which is
contaminated by chemical and organic toxins, according to Mr Evgeni Beliaev,
chief Russian health inspector. He said 10 per cent of food was unhealthy to
eat.
Russians are also dying sooner. Life expectancy fell in 1992 to 69 years for
women and 63 for men, a drop from 1991 figures of 74 years for women and 64
for men. The 25-40 age group is hardest hit by illness and early death.
Nuclear power, according Mr Viktor Danilov-Danilian, the Russian minister
for the environment, poses a greater threat than was previously believed. He
said that the VVR reactors, which make up most of Russia's nuclear power
capacity and which have been considered more safe than the RBMK-type reactor
at Chernobyl, are actually the most dangerous.
Mr Danilov-Danilian was critical of what he described as a weak western
reaction to his nation's woes. The only western environmental aid of note,
he said, was an offer by Norway and Finland to pay Dollars 100m to refit two
nickel plants near their border. But he said Russia would need to contribute
Dollars 550m to make a go of the project, money that Mr Danilov-Danilian
believes could be better spent elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
