<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 92 / Accountancy body changes voting rules
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ELECTION for future presidents of the Institute of Chartered Accountants
in England and Wales will be more democratic than ever before, its ruling
council decided yesterday.
In the first council meeting to be opened to the public, the members
defeated moves to ban canvassing and keep secret the results of voting for
the vice-president, who becomes president automatically after two years.
The monthly meetings of the council have been made public after a debate
over greater accountability within the institute. Voting will continue to be
among members of the council.
</TEXT>
