<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / DTI seeks to wind up travel agent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAVEL PREMIUMS Incor-porated, the UK subsidiary of a US travel company,
closed its London office last month, cancelling the holidays of up to 800
customers who paid in advance, the Department of Trade and Industry said
yesterday.
The DTI said Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, had
presented a petition to the High Court to wind up the company, which was
formed in 1990 and traded in the UK as a travel agent.
The Official Receiver was appointed provisional liquidator by the court
pending determination of the petition, which is expected to be heard in
December.
The DTI said the petition had been presented 'to protect the public interest
from further harm'.
It added: 'We are seeking anyone who has been involved and has paid money to
this company to write to the receivers.'
Trading standards officers in Richmond, south-west London, said they had
been receiving complaints about the company for more than three years. The
company ceased trading on September 18.
Travel Premiums is believed to have provided holidays offered by promotional
companies which were selling timeshare properties and double-glazing.
It is thought that the holidays were offered to people who agreed to attend
sales presentations.
The DTI said that customers should write to the Official Receiver at 21
Bloomsbury Street, London WC1B 3SS, or telephone 071-637 6559.
</TEXT>
