FT  07 OCT 92 / Nigerian poll setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ABUJA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S military rulers yesterday suspended the process of choosing
candidates for December's presidential elections pending the outcome of a
probe into alleged irregularities, Reuter reports from Abuja.
The Armed Forces Ruling Council (AFRC) said after a meeting that the
decision followed a report by the National Electoral Commission on
presidential primaries between September 12 and 26.
'The AFRC has found it necessary to put the primaries and presidential
candidates' nomination processes on hold until all allegations of use of
wealth, falsification of figures, threats, favouritism and all other
electoral malpractices indentified in the NEC report have been thoroughly
investigated and verified,' it said.
Rigging charges following the primaries of the Social Democratic party (SDP)
and National Republican Convention (NRC) - both created by the government -
have cast a shadow over President Ibrahim Babangida's plans to step down on
January 2 after the December 5 presidential election.
