FT  07 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Nader hits at accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Ralph Nader and officials of 11 consumer and environmental groups
yesterday said Nafta was 'so detrimental' the US Congress might be forced to
reject it. They expressed disappointment that Mr Bill Clinton, the
Democratic presidential candidate, had decided not to send the pact back for
renegotiation if elected.
'Clinton does offer an alternative plan that tries to solve environmental
concerns,' said Mr Michael McCloskey, chairman of the Sierra Club. 'Unlike
George Bush, he is willing to link Nafta's successful completion with
environmental safeguards.' The groups challenged the administration's claim
that Nafta was the 'greenest' trade pact.
Criticisms included:
Nafta rests on an assumption that trade will generate wealth, which will
then be used to pay for clean-up; it fails to deem poor environmental rule
enforcement an 'unfair trade practice'; sanitary and phytosanitary standards
still leave legitimate consumer and environmental laws open to challenge as
trade barriers.
</TEXT>
