<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / BR privatisation plans run into difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT proposals for the privatisation of British Rail have run into
serious difficulties over plans to split the ownership of the tracks from
the operation of trains.
The Department of Transport is facing the possibility of rail freight
switching to road, branch lines closing, government subsidies rising and
competition failing to materialise.
Ministers' plans, set out in a white paper in July, are that ownership of
the tracks should be left with a BR residuary body called Railtrack and that
the private sector would take over operation of trains.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, is expected this afternoon to tell
the Conservative party conference that private-sector companies are queueing
up to become train operators once the sell-off legislation has gone through.
But the Department of Transport has yet to tell would-be train operators how
much they will have to pay for access to Railtrack's lines or how much
competition they will face from other companies running the same routes.
In the next few days the department is to test the market, asking potential
train operators to say what services they would like to run and how much
they would be prepared to pay. The results will be fed into a study by the
consultancy arm of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm, which the
government has commissioned to devise a system of charging train operators
for use of the tracks.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand is not expected to produce its report until the end of the
year, but it is understood to have told the Department of Transport that it
has identified a number of serious problems:
Freight traffic could switch from rail to road because some customers may
not be able to afford Railtrack's fees.
Branch lines in Scotland, Wales and Cornwall could close because the system
of charging will expose the scale of their losses to uncomfortable levels of
public scrutiny.
Government subsidies may go up instead of down because private-sector train
operators will cream off lucrative services, leaving the state to subsidise
the loss makers.
Competition between train operators could be almost non-existent because
companies will bid for train service franchises only if they are guaranteed
exclusivity.
The government had hoped to introduce a rail privatisation bill in November
and win royal assent for it by next summer, but the emerging difficulties
threaten to delay the bill into the next session.
Signal failures, Page 18
</TEXT>
