<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Fall in new car sales continues with 4% drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK car industry plunged deeper into gloom yesterday as statistics for
September showed sales of new cars continuing to slide.
Official figures from the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders showed
sales down 4 per cent last month compared with a year ago to 121,823 from
126,906. But many yesterday acknowledged that the underlying situation was
considerably worse.
The market was down by nearly 20 per cent about two thirds of the way
through the month, and the last-minute upsurge is believed to represent
dealer registrations by manufacturers seeking to boost market share. Total
registrations for the first three quarters are 1,297,423 - 2.62 per cent
below last year.
The resumed fall has left manufacturers seeking further ways of tempting
buyers. Ford this week began a price-cutting campaign on 1992 models.
Manufacturers and dealers are wondering whether even market forecasts of
1.55m units this year - down from forecasts of 1.7m or higher made in
January - might not prove optimistic. In spite of economic uncertainty and
political turmoil, some industry leaders were putting on a brave face.
Mr John Towers, managing director of Rover Group, said at the Paris motor
show that sales could recover to 1.65m or even 1.7m units next year. He
said: 'Once we break through the consumer confidence barrier, then quite
clearly there could be a lot of movement in the market.'
Rover was one of the winners last month. It secured a 15.13 per cent market
share, up 4 percentage points on last year, and for the first time in many
months narrowly beat Vauxhall into second place behind Ford.
