<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Former Maxwell director charged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROBERT BUNN, a former finance director of Robert Maxwell's group of
private companies, yesterday became the fourth man to be arrested and
charged with fraud following the Serious Fraud Office investigation into the
collapse of the late publisher's business empire.
Mr Bunn was arrested by City of London police yesterday morning and charged
with a single count of conspiracy to defraud.
He was released on police bail to face City of London magistrates on
December 1. He will appear with Mr Kevin Maxwell, Mr Ian Maxwell, and Mr
Larry Trachtenberg - a financial adviser to Robert Maxwell - who jointly
face 15 counts of theft and conspiracy to defraud involving Pounds 135m.
The full charge against Mr Bunn is that between November 1 1990 and December
31 1991 he conspired with others to defraud a syndicate of 35 banks led by
Swiss Bank Corporation and Credit Lyonnais by knowingly and dishonestly
being a party to the pledging of common stock in Berlitz International Inc
by way of security for loans to third parties in breach of terms of a loan
agree ment dated October 23 1989 between the syndicate and Maxwell
Communication Corporation.
Unlike the June arrests of the two Maxwell brothers and Mr Trachtenberg  -
when police raided the men's homes early in the morning amid a blaze of
publicity - Mr Bunn's arrest, at Snow Hill police station in the City, was
low-key. After his arrest, Mr Bunn, who lives in the City, declined to
comment. 'Mr Bunn will have no comment to make before his trial,' said his
solicitor, Mr Jeffrey Bayes of Burton Copefield.
Mr Bunn, who was finance director of Maxwell Communication Corporation, was
also a director of Bishopsgate Investment management until September 1990.
In May last year he was appointed to the board of London and Bishopsgate
International Investment. Mr Kevin Maxwell yesterday failed in his second
High Court attempt to win a judicial review of the Serious Fraud Office's
refusal to disclose documentary evidence of the case against him.
Mr Maxwell, who faces charges of theft and conspiracy to defraud, had
claimed the SFO was acting unlawfully and unfairly in not disclosing such
evidence before questioning him under powers which remove the right to
silence.
</TEXT>
