<PROFILE>_AN-CJGCCAEBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921007
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Advertising by banks 'wasted'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS and building societies are wasting millions of pounds a year on
advertising, Mintel, the market research group, claims in a report published
today.
It says that customers are more influenced by other factors. For example,
Mintel says, most people choose their bank or building society according to
its location or the recommendation of a friend rather than as a result of
advertising.
Mintel says in a report compiled from a survey of 1,000 adults that 43 per
cent of account holders base their choice of bank or building society on its
proximity to their homes. Two out of five chose the same institutions as
their parents, 15 per cent listened to the recommendation of a friend and
only 5 per cent said they were affected by advertising or by direct
mailshots.
Mintel found, that people aged 15 to 19 are more likely than other age
groups to be influenced by advertising, with 13 per cent admitting they were
affected by advertising. However 32 per cent said they chose the same bank
as their parents.
The importance for the banks and building societies in catching customers
when they are young is borne out by the survey, which showed that most
people stayed with the institution at which they first opened an account.
Customer Service in Personal Finance, Myth or Reality? Mintel International
Group, 18-19 Long Lane, London EC1A 9HE. Pounds 895.
</TEXT>
