FT  07 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Buying costs clip Manchester United 6% to
Pounds 5.06m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPENDING on players reduced pre-tax profit at Manchester United, the Premier
League football club, by 6 per cent in its first full year as a quoted
company.
Although profit before transfer fees went up by 24 per cent to Pounds 7.68m
(Pounds 6.18m), net spending of Pounds 2.63m (Pounds 801,000) on players -
including defender Paul Parker and goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel - cut the
pre-tax outcome to Pounds 5.06m (Pounds 5.38m).
To draw attention to the fact that the players represent an investment,
rather than simply a drain on profits, United said it had commissioned an
independent valuation by Touche Ross, the accountants, which estimated that
the squad was worth Pounds 24m. Not that this figure was being put on the
balance sheet, said Mr Martin Edwards, chief executive and holder of 28 per
cent of the shares.
Mr Robin Launders, finance director, suggested that the share price, which
rose from 282p to 289p yesterday (still 96p below the flotation price), was
discounting net spending of at least Pounds 2m on players this year. So far
the Pounds 1m paid out for striker Dion Dublin (who has since broken his
leg) has been balanced by disposals.
With a further Pounds 250,000 added to the transfer reserve, it could
support spending of Pounds 3.35m on players.
Turnover in the year to July 31 rose 13 per cent to Pounds 20.1m thanks to
higher attendances - the average gate for league games at Old Trafford was
45,000 - and higher prices. Gate receipts rose to Pounds 11.1m (Pounds
9.2m).
Income from sponsorship, catering and the club shop rose by between 9 and 14
per cent.
The only decline came in television revenue, from Pounds 2.34m to Pounds
1.84m.
Mr Edwards said that the club had totted up 110 hours of television the
previous year, when it won the European Cup Winners Cup. This year the
Premier League deal with BSkyB, the satellite broadcaster, would bring in
about Pounds 1.8m. Other television income might add another Pounds 1m.
Operating profit advanced by 8 per cent to Pounds 6.26m (Pounds 5.79m).
Interest income rose to Pounds 1.42m (Pounds 385,000) and the amount of cash
held increased to Pounds 14.8m (Pounds 14.1m). This was after capital
spending of nearly Pounds 4m, including the first Pounds 2m of an estimated
Pounds 10m on the new Stretford End stand.
Mr Launders said that this season building work has reduced capacity from
47,000 to less than 34,000. However, price rises and the reduction in the
number of cheaper terrace tickets had raised the average match revenue per
person from Pounds 9 to Pounds 13.10. Next season the capacity would rise
again to 43,000.
A final dividend of 12p makes a total of 18p, compared with 17.4p forecast
at flotation. Earnings per share improved from 17.8p to 27.6p after the
transfer fund appropriation, or to 29.7p, compared with 37p, before it.
See Observer
