<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Texaco's Canary Wharf move is on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEXACO, the international oil company, yesterday announced that its UK
headquarters will, after all, move to Canary Wharf. One thousand employees
will move to the London Docklands office complex in the first quarter of
next year.
The lease signed by Texaco is a boost for the insolvent office scheme that
cost more than Pounds 1.5bn to build. It has suffered a succession of
setbacks in recent weeks including the withdrawal of American Express and
Chemical Bank, two of its most prominent tenants.
Mr Alan Bloom, a joint administrator, said that attracting an international
tenant of the standing of Texaco 'will provide a significant boost to our
efforts to ensure the scheme's viability'.
The agreement followed months of negotiations that started when Canary Wharf
went into administration in May. Shortly afterwards Texaco postponed the
move to Canary Wharf that it had planned for August, saying that it was
'determined to ensure our relocation is conducted at the right time, in the
right way and on the right terms'. Texaco said it was pleased with its new
agreement, which met its 'requirements for a headquarters appropriate to the
company's long-term needs'.
The company's decision to move into Canary Wharf reduces Barclays Bank's
Pounds 200m exposure to the project by an estimated Pounds 60m, as the bank
had acted as a third party guarantor for Texaco's lease. Texaco is believed
to have paid about Pounds 30m for a 1,000-year lease on a 230,000 sq ft
building at 1 Westferry Circus, with an option to buy the building or break
the lease after six years. It will also rent an extra 30,000 sq ft on two
floors at 7 Westferry Circus, the adjacent building.
Texaco's decision was not affected by uncertainty surrounding the future of
the extension of London Underground's Jubilee Line to east London. 'Although
we would like the Jubilee Line extension to be built, we have made our
decision on the strength of transport links that are already there,' Texaco
said. 'We always had in mind that the Jubilee Line would not be in place
until the mid to late 1990s.'
</TEXT>
