<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Tax body warns of poor legislation: Budget Submission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIME between the Budget and the legislation arising from it should be
extended to curb poorly drafted legislation, the Institute of Taxation has
warned.
The institute, which represents tax professionals, said in its annual
representation on the Budget to the Inland Revenue that there had been a
decline in the quality of legislation in the past few years.
It said government proposals on reform of the Budget would reduce the period
during which tax legislation is open for discussion from 90 days to 70 days
and would increase the risk of poor legislation. The institute said the
finance bill should be published in January, but with its second and third
readings as at present in order to extend the consultation period.
It also backed the idea of a technical financial bill outside the normal
Budget timetable. Mr Ian Luder, chairman of the institute's technical
committee said: 'This is a golden opportunity to improve the quality of
legislation,' He said some recent attempts to introduce legislation had been
'farcical'.
The institute also criticised the growing use of extra-statutory concessions
and statements of practice as a substitute for legislation.
</TEXT>
