<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party At Brighton: Baker joins rebel ranks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH BAKER form-ally joined the ranks of the Tory backbench rebels
yesterday, making clear that, without significant changes to the text of the
Maastricht treaty, he would not support government efforts to ratify it.
But he was challenged by Mr Kenneth Clarke, his successor as home secretary,
over whether or not he opposed Britain's entry into the European exchange
rate mechanism two years ago.
Speaking on BBC Radio 4, Mr Clarke asserted that 'in the end' only Baroness
Thatcher and Lord Ridley were against entry. 'If any of the others were
against it, they fooled me,' he said.
In Mr Baker's words, however: 'I argued against it and against going in at
DM2.95. I lost, but I was assured that there would be flexibility.'
Britain was 'well out of' the European exchange rate mechanism, he argued
later, saying the government must choose between floating exchange rates and
a single currency, and that he would prefer the first of these options.
Leading a number of leading Euro-sceptics on the conference fringe
yesterday, Mr Baker outlined his reservations to Maastricht on subsidiarity,
Commission powers and border controls, telling his packed audience he saw
little prospect of amendments being adopted that would enable him to support
ratification.
'It seems unlikely to me that these conditions on these three matters . .
will be met,' he said. 'I don't believe that they can be fulfilled.'
Questioned later, he said that if there were no changes, 'then I will not
support the treaty'.
Clearly relishing life outside the cabinet, Mr Baker called for European
commissioners to be replaced by heads of department 'rather like the
permanent secretaries of our own ministries'. These would simply execute
decisions taken by the council of ministers and would not have 'their own
political agendas'.
On the domestic economy, he called for an immediate 1 point cut in interest
rates 'with a target of 6 per cent within a matter of months.'
He predicted: 'Even after interest rate cuts, inflation in Britain next
spring could be below 3 per cent.'
Elsewhere, Lord Tebbit characterised the Maastricht treaty as 'a timebomb'
threatening to 'destroy utterly' what the Community's founding fathers set
out to create.
Speaking before his galvanic address to conference, he said that if there
was not a UK referendum, voters would believe the democratic system did not
work - and 'that is the language of the National Front'.
Mr John Biffen, another former cabinet minister, predicted: 'The fight you
have seen taking place in this conference will go on and on and on,'
claiming that Euro-scepticism was 'no longer the gift of a handful of rather
romantic Tory MPs'.
Sir Teddy Taylor, MP for Southend East, was on the rampage, claiming there
would be no point in voting at the next general election if Maastricht were
ratified.
'Our liberty is almost gone, this would be the end,' he said, also calling
for a referendum on the treaty.
'(The people's) advice and approval is needed before we sign.'
</TEXT>
