<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party At Brighton: Tebbit electrifies
anti-Maastricht forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEEP divisions within the Conservative party over Maastricht were
brutally exposed by Lord Tebbit yesterday as he seized on the debate on
Europe to press the government to abandon ratification of the treaty.
In an electrifying address the former party chairman won round after round
of passionate applause from the treaty's opponents and provoked charges of
'Brutus' from Tory MEPs.
But his rabble-rousing oratory and undisguised criticisms of Mr John Major
were met with a calm and dextrous counter-attack from Mr Douglas Hurd, who
warned that the party risked breaking itself over Europe.
'Let us decide to give that madness a miss,' he said to widespread applause.
The foreign secretary's forthright defence of the government's achievements
in the Maastricht negotiations - widely praised as a masterful performance -
ensured that the highly vocal anti-treaty faction was defeated by an
estimated margin of about 4 to 1 on an innocuous motion.
The wording congratulated the government on its European Community
presidency alongside an amendment seeking reforms to halt 'unnecessary
interference from Brussels' and a more open, accountable community.
Prior to the debate, many Conservatives had claimed that newspaper reports
of a deep schism within the party on Maastricht were false. In the event,
the ferocity of the head-on clash between opponents and supporters of
Maastricht was far greater than any had predicted.
Speaker after speaker sought, amid a cacophony of cheers and boos, to
polarise the party between government loyalists and the distinctly more
vociferous rebels.
In their opening speeches, the movers sought to shut down the controversy by
insisting that the enforcement of subsidiarity rules - devolving powers as
closely as possible to those they could effect - would rectify the treaty's
weaknesses.
That hope was abruptly brushed aside when Dr Bernard Juby of Birmingham
Yardley declared to a roar: 'The Maastricht treaty is dead - the Danes saw
to that.'
His theme was taken up and expanded when Lord Tebbit was welcomed to the
platform with delegates on their feet in many parts of the hall.
As a grim-faced platform looked on, the one-time Chingford MP offered curt
congratulation to Mr Major's election victory, before going on to warn that
the government was now 'in desperate trouble' with Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, under attack even in the normally loyal Conservative press.
Then, in a clear sideswipe at the prime minister, who oversaw the UK's entry
into the exchange rate mechanism, he added: 'I hope you will stand by your
chancellor - it was not Norman Lamont's decision to enter the ERM. He did
his best to make the unworkable work.
'The cost in lost jobs, bankrupt firms, repossessed homes, in the terrible
wounds inflicted on industry, has been savage.'
Lord Tebbit then set about Maastricht, claiming that 'a great tide of
opinion' opposed to a federal community was engulfing Europe.
With a direct challenge to Mr Major to 'raise the flags of patriots of all
the states of Europe', he called on the prime minister to launch the drive
for a treaty with 'no mention of more power for Brussels, no mention of
economic, monetary and political union.'
But Lord Tebbit was not without his critics. Immediately he sat down, Mrs
Pamela Parker from East Surrey won applause from elsewhere in the hall when
she declared her fury with his stance, warning that he was offering
'political suicide'.
As opponents demanded a referendum, other loyalists underlined that the
country would suffer dire consequences for industry if it abandoned Europe.
Mr Malcolm Harbour from Solihull said thousands of jobs had been created by
foreign investment and Britain was at the heart of Europe.
Critics should 'go out into the streets of Sunderland and argue that they do
not want the jobs created by us being at the heart of Europe,' he said.
When Mr Hurd rose, his appeal was for cool heads. He stressed common ground
in the party pointing out that very few opposed EC membership or advocated a
European super-state.
'We are winning the arguments - now is not the time to kick over the table,'
he said.
Mr Hurd then went on to put the argument for Britain maintaining the stance
it had taken prior to the election and in Commons' votes since.
'We don't want Britain to be on the sidelines when the security and
prosperity of Europe are being decided.
'We know in our bones it's not safe, it's not wise, it's not right.'
The foreign secretary promised that an explanatory booklet explaining the
treaty would be made available and promised he would seek to establish ways
of minimising interference by Brussels and means of increasing openness in
decision-making.
Summing up, Mr Hurd evoked what was once dubbed the white man's burden,
concluding: 'In the name of that tradition . . I ask for your support as we
extend and strengthen the effort which we, the British, make for a safer and
more decent world.'
His ovation was duly granted him.
</TEXT>
