FT  07 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party At Brighton: Chancellor to emphasise
fight against inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the chancellor, will use his speech tomorrow to emphasise
the government's determination to defeat inflation.
Normally, the annual gathering of the Tory faithful would not be considered
a suitable audience for an exposition of government economic policy. But in
a break with tradition the chancellor is expected to devote a substantial
part of his speech to policy questions to counter widespread criticism
following sterling's departure from the European exchange rate mechanism
three weeks ago.
During tomorrow's debate on the economy, Mr Lamont will develop his idea of
using a number of financial indicators, encompassing measures of narrow and
broad money supply growth, asset prices including house prices and the
exchange rate, to determine monetary policy. He will also underline the
government's wish to get a grip on the UK's rapidly growing public sector
borrowing requirement through control of public expenditure rather than any
increase in taxation.
However, Mr Lamont is likely to avoid giving a very detailed description of
the government's policy stance tomorrow. His meeting next Monday with the
Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee will provide a better
opportunity for expounding macro-economic policy, while the annual Mansion
House speech to the City on October 29 is still seen as the occasion for
giving a comprehensive analysis of monetary policy.
Government officials yesterday insisted that sterling's sharp fall since
Black Wednesday was not a sign that the government was turning away from
tight policies designed to reduce inflation.
</TEXT>
