FT  07 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party At Brighton: Tube extension set to be
shelved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROPOSED extension of the Jubilee Line to London's Docklands is set to
join the lengthening list of casualties of the toughest public spending
round since the early 1980s.
Ministers at the Conservative conference said yesterday that the Treasury
now looked certain to win its battle to have the project shelved, if not
scrapped, in the wake of the collapse of the Canary Wharf development.
Only an unconditional offer from the banks now administering the Docklands
development to meet in full the Pounds 400m private sector contribution
promised by Olympia &amp; York could rescue the project.
A final decision to shelve the project, yielding a Pounds 1.5bn saving for
the Treasury, could be made as early as next week at a meeting of the
cabinet committee chaired by Lord Wakeham.
As ministers acknowledged that the government was still struggling to meet
the Pounds 244.5bn spending target agreed for next year, Mr William
Waldegrave, the minister responsible for the Citizen's Charter, announced a
big extension of the market-testing of Whitehall services.
In an effort to square the circle of tight spending constraints and improved
public services, he said that the politics of the 'growth of government'
were dead.
Instead, he said, the improvement in the quality of public services offered
by the charter would help 'end the false choice between low rates of
taxation and higher standards of service'.
Mr Waldegrave said that, as part of the drive for efficiency, more than
Pounds 1bn-worth of services now delivered by civil servants in Whitehall
would be market-tested this year by inviting private sector competition.
The sharp increase from a figure of only Pounds 25m last year would mean
that a whole range of professional services such as accountancy and
information technology would join more traditional services such as security
and catering in being exposed to private-sector disciplines.
Mr Waldegrave's speech also followed predictions from senior ministers that
the government may face a 'spring of discontent' from public sector unions
next year in response to draconian measures to hold down the government's
pay bill.
The ministers said that the cabinet committee reviewing the allocation of
next year's Pounds 244.5bn Whitehall budget would not set a formal pay
'norm' for the public sector. But most workers could expect increases of
between zero and 3 per cent.
Despite the proposed scrapping of the Jubilee line extension, Mr Waldegrave
said that the government was aiming to protect as many as possible of those
of its investment programmes than directly affected demand in the private
sector - particularly the construction industry.
</TEXT>
