FT  07 OCT 92 / The Conservative Party At Brighton: Party chairman appeals
for unity and resolve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG appeal for the unity and resolution that characterised the Tory
party in the 1980s came yesterday from Sir Norman Fowler, the party
chairman.
With the prime minister facing growing divisions on Europe and the economy,
Sir Norman acknowledged that the conference was about future issues. He
said: 'We stand or fall as one party. We have won more elections than any
other party in Britain because we are the most united and most determined
party in Britain.'
In his first conference speech as party chairman, Sir Norman said that the
lesson of the Thatcher years was that the Tories' electoral successes had
come from their discipline and determination to keep to long-term aims.
'Over the same period Labour have been the most divided and most
undisciplined party in Britain. We should not contemplate going down their
road - the socialist road of division,' he warned.
'That is why they have lost . . and lost again.'
'The lesson is that we must all stand together, and I do mean all: in our
branches, in our associations, in our areas, in our local councils and yes,
if I may say so, among our MPs at Westminster too.
'In this hall and across the country there are thousands of people who
worked themselves to the bone on the doorsteps and pavements of Britain to
get this party elected. We must stay true to them.'
Speaking just a couple of hours ahead of yesterday afternoon's debate on
Europe, he reminded the conference of the setbacks and hard times in the
early 1980s over controversial issues such as trade union reforms and the
first privatisations.
There was vigorous applause from delegates when his call for party unity
explicitly included MPs, a few of whom have irritated some rank and file
party members by their open rebellion on the Maastricht treaty.
Sir Norman said that the question of Britain's future in Europe was one of
the three great issues for the 1990s. He used rhetoric reminiscent of the
Euro-sceptics to emphasise the government's commitment to oppose a federal
Europe and its goal of 'a Europe of nation states where decisions are taken
as close as possible to the people'.
His speech also aimed to remind the conference of the debt owed to Mr John
Major for the election victory - which Sir Norman described as a 'personal
triumph' for the prime minister.
The applause was, however, at least as loud for the mention of Lady Thatcher
as 'one of the great leaders of our party'.
