<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Holding tight on a roller-coaster ride: The currency turmoil
since Black Wednesday is unlikely to ease until economic policy is clear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN EXCHANGE markets do not seem to know what to do with Britain's
devalued currency. But Britain's exporters cannot afford simply to wait and
see where sterling eventually ends up. Their marketing strategies and
expected profits depend on estimates made now about where the pound will be
both in three months and three years.
So where might the pound end once the excitement dies down? And what kind of
rollercoaster ride can sterling expect on the foreign exchanges in the
meantime?
Economists like to believe that exchange rates are determined according to
the predictions of their economic theories. The daily gyrations in the
markets may be the result of market speculators and the interventions of
central banks. But, in the medium term, all this market noise should wash
out leaving economic 'fundamentals' to determine the currency's value.
Typically, though, economists disagree about which 'fundamental' forces
count. Take two apparently simple questions. Was sterling overvalued in the
European exchange rate mechanism at a central rate of DM2.95? Is it now
undervalued relative to other European currencies at around DM2.40? Ask a
group of economists and you will get at least as many different answers as
economists.
Those who said that sterling was correctly valued at DM2.95 were using the
'purchasing power parity' valuation method. This says that the correct
exchange rate between any two currencies is the one which equalises the
price of the same traded item in both countries. If cars are cheaper in one
country, then traders should buy them and export them to make a profit. But
this will push up that country's exchange rate until price parity is
restored.
The charts show purchasing power parity exchange rates for the UK, US and
Germany over the past decade. They are based on a basket of similar goods
compiled by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development and
use trade-weighted exchange rates. They suggest that sterling was overvalued
before Black Wednesday on September 16 - UK exports were, on average
slightly more expensive than those of competitors.
But the effective 11 per cent devaluation of sterling has more than
eliminated this disadvantage - it is now 6 per cent undervalued in
trade-weighted terms. And its previous overvaluation was largely due to the
undervaluation of the US dollar, as the US chart shows. Calculations by
Goldman Sachs, the investment bank, suggest that sterling is now undervalued
 -by 14 per cent against the overvalued D-Mark and by 3 per cent against the
French franc.
Does this mean that sterling must eventually appreciate against European
currencies or alternatively that UK inflation must be higher than elsewhere
to bring UK export prices into line? The track record of purchasing power
parity rates suggests not. They have, in fact, been a very poor guide to
actual exchange-rate valuations over the past decade.
The reason is that purchasing power parity calculations ignore many other
economic 'fundamentals' other than export prices which determine whether a
country's exchange rate is sustainably valued. To compete with German
manufacturers at DM2.95, UK exporters had to sell their goods at comparable
prices. But there were too few UK exporters who were able to do so at that
exchange rate. So Britain is left with a relatively small and unprofitable
export sector and a trade deficit at the bottom of a recession as a result.
The alternative method - called 'fundamental equilibrium exchange rates' to
scare off the uninitiated - uses macroeconomic models to estimate the
exchange rate at which the economy can return the trade account into rough
balance in the medium term. The fundamental equilibrium charts tell a very
different tale. They suggest, in direct contradiction to the purchasing
power parity figures, that the D-Mark has been consistently undervalued over
the past decade, as its large trade surpluses suggested. The US dollar is
undervalued in purchasing power parity terms but correctly valued using the
fundamental equilibrium method.
In fundamental equilibrium terms, sterling was overvalued at DM2.95 - by
about 15 per cent according to Mr Ray Barrell at the National Institute of
Economic and Social Research. The institute argued in October 1990 that
sterling should enter the ERM at a lower rate. But sterling's subsequent
fall since Black Wednesday to around DM2.40 means that it is now correctly
valued. Enough British exporters can have a profitable existence to balance
the current account so long as the competitive gains are not frittered away
in higher inflation.
Yet even if the current exchange rate is an acceptable final resting place
for sterling, the chances are high that it will have to fall further in the
meantime.
Why must sterling overshoot? UK interest rates are already lower than in
most other European countries and are expected to fall further. Investors
will continue to hold sterling only if they can also expect capital gains
from an appreciation of the currency. So sterling must fall far enough so
that it can both appreciate and arrive back at a reasonable resting place.
But how large must this overshoot be? The farther that markets expect
sterling interest rates to fall relative to those in continental Europe, the
farther traders must push sterling down. That is why the lack of a clearly
articulated government economic strategy is destabilising.
The chances are that currency analysts have been studying the behaviour of
policymakers in the US, Australia, New Zealand and Canada, using charts such
as those shown, to gain some clues as to how the Treasury might act. These
are the countries which, like the UK, have experienced serious debt-related
recessions. They have all responded by cutting short-term interest rates
aggressively, in all cases below those in Germany.
Far from leading to a build-up of inflationary pressure, they have also seen
inflation and long-term interest rates fall relative to those in Germany.
The cost has been large exchange-rate depreciations against the D-Mark, in
all cases at least twice as large as sterling's fall so far.
Will the UK take the same route? The gain would be a relief for hard-pressed
consumers and bankers. The risk is that a temporary fall in sterling towards
DM2.00 would encourage Britain's famed inflationary tendencies. But unless
the government speaks out soon, the markets are likely to anticipate that
more cuts in interest rates are coming - and sell sterling accordingly.
</TEXT>
