<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Pounds troubles blamed as Sanyo sheds jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SANYO ELECTRIC Manufac-turing (UK), a subsidiary of the Japanese electronics
group, said yesterday that the weakness of sterling against the yen had
contributed to a decision to shed about 95 jobs - a third of the workforce -
at its microwave ovens plant at Newton Aycliffe, County Durham.
The company, which buys some components from Japanese suppliers other than
Sanyo, said the yen's relative strength and high interest rates had worsened
problems caused by the recession.
The 'difficult decision' to restructure at the Newton Aycliffe plant, which
formed part of an Pounds 11m investment in the region announced only four
years ago, was necessary to ensure it survived.
Mr Ron Bell, assistant to the plant's managing director, said: 'We're trying
to re-establish ourselves in a very competitive market.'
The Newton Aycliffe plant has been selling 70 per cent of its output in the
UK and the rest in continental Europe. Mr Bell said hopes of an imminent end
to the recession had not been realised. The floating of the pound had not
helped investor confidence, he added.
The investment in the region, for which Sanyo received substantial UK
government regional grant aid, was expected in 1988 to create more than 500
jobs.
It was greeted as an example of the region's economic regeneration through
Japanese investment. Sanyo employs 283 people at Newton Aycliffe and 24 at
its magnetron plant at Thornaby-on-Tees, Cleveland, which is not affected by
the job cuts.
The EETPU section of the AEEU engineering and electrical union has
single-union status at the Newton Aycliffe plant where a pendulum
arbitration agreement - in effect a no-strike deal - is in force.
Consultation with the union on the job losses has begun.
