of that by Warburg Pincus, the US investment bank which had fully
underwritten it.
'We are not surprised that the take-up from institutions has been very low,
given the current market conditions and the pricing of the issue; any issue
priced at 55p against a stock price of 16p is not likely to go forward very
well,' the group said. The shares traded at a peak of 215p in October 1991.
In voting right terms there are now 200m shares in issue; 30 per cent are
held by SFEC, a company controlled by Mr Gilbert Gross, honorary president
of Aegis; 30 per cent by Warburg Pincus; 6 per cent by Eurocom; and the rest
by various financial institutions including Fidelity and Philips and Drew.
The two principal shareholders each have two representatives on the board.
