FT  07 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Savage Pounds 2m back in the black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAVAGE Group is reaping the rewards of its two-year reorganisation of
European businesses with a return to the black in the year to June 30.
Yesterday the USM-quoted hardware group announced pre-tax profits of Pounds
2.02m, against losses of Pounds 115,000 previously. It is also returning to
the dividend list with a 0.25p payment and expects that, if it is possible,
an interim will be paid for the current half-year.
Mr Doug Rogers, who became chairman in the wake of a shareholder revolt in
autumn 1990, said: 'We have reduced the company to a solid base from where
it can grow.' Pre-tax profits in continuing activities rose 57 per cent to
Pounds 2.23m (Pounds 1.42m).
When he arrived the balance of Savage's business was half UK and half
Europe. Now it was 75 per cent UK, 15 per cent Germany and 5 per cent each
for Benelux and the rest of the world.
Mr Rogers said that recent interest rate cuts and the fall in sterling
against other currencies reinforced the board's cautious optimism about the
UK performance in particular and the maintenance of the group's recovery in
general.
Total turnover fell to Pounds 73.5m (Pounds 123.9m), though in continuing
activities it rose 1 per cent to Pounds 69.4m (Pounds 68.8m). There were no
exceptional costs (Pounds 494,000) and total interest charges fell to Pounds
1.34m (Pounds 4.09m). There was an extraordinary charge of Pounds 2.85m
(Pounds 5.13m). Earnings emerged at 0.9p (losses 5.4p).
