<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Iraqi Kurds attack PKK camps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RIVAL Kurdish factions in northern Iraq were reported yesterday to be
engaged in a major clash, as Iraqi peshmerga fighters attempted to expel
rebel Turkish Kurds from their bases near the border.
The incident provides the first indication of the tacit co-operation of the
Iraqi Kurds in Turkey's conflict with the PKK, the Marxist guerrillas waging
an increasingly violent separatist campaign.
The attack follows warnings from the Iraq Kurdish Front to the PKK, which
has stepped up attacks on Turkish government positions since the Gulf war.
The presence of PKK forces in northern Iraq has threatened relations between
Turkey and the newly established Kurdish administration in northern Iraq.
Iraqi Kurds depend on aid supplied via Turkey.
Details of the fighting remain sketchy but one Turkish official confirmed a
'major clash' was happening Kurdish officials said their forces were
attacking three PKK camps near the town of Zakho. Aid workers in the area
said there were heavy casualties with local hospitals said to be
overflowing. Around 6,000 peshmergas were engaging 3,000 PKK guerrillas near
the villages of Shirwan and Hakuk.
Ankara remains anxious that the evolution of a de facto Kurdish state in
northern Iraq will encourage Turkey's Kurds to step up demands for
independence.
Meanwhile Iraqi Kurds fear Turkey's struggle with the PKK could imperil
allied air protection, which remains dependent on Turkish approval.
</TEXT>
