<PROFILE>_AN-CJGCCAADFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921007
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Treasury discusses proposals for more open style
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY has unveiled far-reaching proposals to meet criticisms that it
has made serious mistakes over economic policy and become remote from the
City and industry.
The initiative could lead to a more open style at Whitehall's most important
department, whose reputation has been severely dented during Britain's
longest recession for 50 years.
One plan under consideration would lead to non-government economists being
asked to work on Treasury forecasts to improve their accuracy, in the
biggest shake-up at the Treasury since the early 1980s.
Other ideas being considered include:
Greater efforts to recruit people with experience in industry and financial
markets, possibly by increasing salaries for specific individuals.
Paying companies to undertake studies in areas such as financial
deregulation.
Less secrecy in internal discussion of proposed policy changes, for instance
over taxation, as part of a new policy to encourage wider swapping of ideas
with the private sector.
Revamping procedures for making economic forecasts, which in the past two
years have turned out to be optimistic.
Sir Terry Burns, Treasury permanent secretary, presented the ideas at an
unpublicised meeting of the Treasury's top 70 officials on Monday, held at
the Institution of Civil Engineers in central London.
The proposals are being drawn up as the Treasury attempts to find a new
economic strategy after the shock of Britain's exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism three weeks ago.
The Treasury's tactics in attempting to defend the pound ahead of ERM
suspension have been widely criticised in the City. The department has also
come under attack from politicians and industrialists for misjudging the
seriousness of the recession.
Sir Terry's ideas are being presented as a 'green paper' for internal
debate, and lack detail.
They may need to be refined after discussions with ministers, who may be
worried that less Treasury secrecy could lead to more potentially
embarrassing 'leaks' about details of policy actions.
That could involve drawing more on ideas about how the economy is
progressing from people in industry and the City, possibly by paying such
individuals for specific aspects of forecasting.
Steps may also be taken to improve training and flexibility among the 1,500
employees in the central policymaking departments.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
