<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 92 / Scottish Widows ordered to review 20,000 life policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH WIDOWS, one of the UK's largest insurance companies, has been
ordered by the Life Assurance and Unit Trust Regulatory Organisation to
inform more than 20,000 policyholders that they may have been sold the wrong
policy.
The policies were sold by Scottish Widows' tied agents - financial advisers
which sell the products of one company exclusively but which are not
directly employed by it.
A compliance check by Lautro, which started in April, discovered that some
sales agents had gathered too little information on policyholders to be able
to offer best advice, as required by industry regulators. Scottish Widows is
checking policies sold by all its tied agency firms.
Mr Robert Hogarth, Scottish Widows' compliance manager, resigned in July
after the investigation began. Scottish Widows, which sold just under
129,000 policies last year, is one of the UK's top 10 performing life
insurance and pensions houses.
The activities of tied agents have been a particular concern for Lautro
which has targeted that category of sales agent for special review.
Up to 45 per cent of policies sold via 'direct' or 'tied' agents are
terminated within the first two years of the contract, compared with only 22
to 32 per cent of policies sold through independent financial advisers,
according to data from the Securities and Investments Board, the chief
regulatory watchdog.
Scottish Widows says its preliminary review of all 27,000 policies sold by
tied agents since it first recruited them in February 1989 found only 6,200
were completely satisfactory. In another 3,240 cases, an unsuitable policy
may have been sold.
In the remaining 17,500 cases, there is not enough information for Scottish
Widows and Lautro to decide whether best advice was given and a suitable
product sold.
Scottish Widows is writing to more than 20,000 policyholders, inviting those
who may have an inappropriate policy to consult one of the company's own
agents. Policyholders on whom not enough information is available will be
asked to fill in a short questionnaire detailing their financial
circumstances.
The company has promised Lautro that its full review of the policies will be
completed by November 30.
Mr Newton Scott, general manager, marketing and sales at Scottish Widows,
said the company had reduced the number of tied agency firms it used to 143
from 184 at the end of last year. 'Some firms were not capable of producing
enough quality business. Some are not complying and are not meeting the sort
of standards we wanted,' he said.
Scottish Widows sells 90 per cent of its policies through IFAs but is trying
to create a direct sales force which is scheduled to be in place at the
beginning of next year.
In cases where an unsuitable product is found to have been sold, Scottish
Widows will try to replace the policy with a more suitable one.
If it does not have a suitable policy available or if a life product was not
the best form of investment for the client, the company is obliged by the
Financial Services Act to restore them to the financial situation they would
have been in had they not taken the contract.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
