FT  06 OCT 92 / Unita quits joint force in Angola
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUANDA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNITA, Angola's former rebel movement, withdrew from the country's newly
formed joint armed forces yesterday in protest at what it called fraud in
the country's first multi-party elections last week, agencies report from
Luanda.
The move came just hours after Mr Paulo Alcides Mango, the organisation's
secretary-general, called on the National Electoral Council to halt
publication of election results. 'If it does not, the (council) will have to
accept fully what will happen in the country,' he said.
A western diplomat said: 'This is very grave, one of many moves in a very
complicated game.'
Unita has about 3,000 soldiers in the newly unified armed forces. But it has
25,000-30,000 fighters being demobilised in 22 assembly areas across the
country who could easily be rearmed.
</TEXT>
