<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Senate overrides Bush's veto of cable TV bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEN WARN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Senate yesterday overrode President George Bush's refusal to sign a
bill regulating the cable television industry in its first successful
challenge of the presidential veto since Mr Bush came into office. Congress
has failed to muster the two-thirds majority needed to overturn Mr Bush's
veto on 35 previous occasions.
Despite last-minute lobbying of senators by Mr Bush, the Senate voted by 74
to 25 with one abstention to back the legislation, which would empower the
Federal Communications Commission to set 'reasonable' rates for basic cable
services, except in the few districts where cable operators already face
competition.
The House was also due to vote on the legislation again, which it originally
passed by 280 votes to 128, or by more than the necessary two-thirds margin.
Since de-regulation in 1984 prices for basic cable services have risen by
more than 50 per cent. Broadcast television and consumer groups have mounted
extensive advertising campaigns backing the legislation and attacking what
they see as the cable companies' exploitation of monopoly positions in many
districts.
The tussle over the cable legislation had become a test of political
strength in the final weeks ahead of the US presidential election. While
debate over the issue sometimes cut across party lines, Mr Bush's opposition
to the bill allowed Democrats to paint him as siding with the interests of
the cable industry against the consumer.
However, Mr Bush opposed the legislation on the grounds that regulation of
the industry would push up, rather than cut, cable rates because of
provisions laying down service standards and requiring cable companies to
negotiate with broadcasting stations before carrying their signals. The
legislation would 'cost American jobs and discourage investment in
telecommunications,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
