<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Ireland to help exporters hit by
slide in the pound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Irish government is to announce support measures today for exporters who
have been badly hit by sterling's continuing slide on the foreign exchange
markets, but Mr Albert Reynolds, the prime minister, again ruled out
devaluation as a policy option.
Yesterday sterling fell to a new record low of Pounds 1.10 against the punt,
which prompted Mr Terry Hobdell, the chairman of the Irish Small Firms
Association (SFA), to say: 'This issue calls for immediate action by the
government. It is a serious crisis, not just for exporters but for
manufacturers who face the problem of much cheaper imports from the UK.'
He said the SFA is looking for a package of around IPounds 150-200m 'to
underwrite exporters and those facing competition from the UK'. The
government said IPounds 50m was to be made available, along with IPounds
25m, from EC structural funds. The package is expected to include direct
employment subsidies and selective reductions in employers' national
insurance contributions.
Although the financial markets anticipate a punt devaluation, all the main
economic lobby groups continue to back the defence of the punt, including
unions. A spokesman for SIPTU, Ireland's largest trade union, said
yesterday: 'Special supports for those worst-hit by sterling's weakness will
be cheaper and better for the country than devaluation.'
</TEXT>
