<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: The British PM explains goals -
Major's letter to EC leaders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The following are key excerpts from the letter sent last Friday by Mr John
Major, UK prime minister, to other EC leaders. In it he explains why EC
finance ministers will not be present at next week's emergency summit
meeting in Birmingham. He also outlines the British presidency's goals.
'A number of colleagues have expressed willingness to have a general
discussion at Birmingham of the recent turbulence on the foreign exchanges
and about the lessons we need to draw.
'Some of you have, however, expressed concern that if finance ministers are
present that would arouse expectations of immediate decisions and could
itself create market instability. I am very happy to respond to that concern
and do not propose to invite finance ministers to join us. It would not be
credible, however, in the light of very dramatic and far-reaching events, to
have no discussion at all of these events when we meet.'
Mr Major said he wanted the summit to agree a declaration covering: greater
openness in the Community business; more consultation by the European
Commission before making proposals for legislation; steps to remove peoples'
concern at the loss of national identity by making a reality of the concept
of subsidiarity; greater involvement by national parliaments at an early
stage in Community decision-making; increasing the appeal of the Maastricht
treaty by showing how it affects the lives of ordinary people for the
better, for example greater freedom of movement, consular protection,
educational exchanges and an improved environment.
'The Community has been through a rocky patch,' Mr Major said. 'I believe
that at Birmingham we can give a new and united signal showing both that we
have responded to public opinion and how we will bring the Community closer
to the lives of our citizens.'
</TEXT>
