<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 92 / Consumer prices soar in Turkey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER prices in Turkey rose 7.4 per cent in September, the highest rate
since January, according to the state institute of statistics, writes John
Murray Brown in Istanbul.
The rise was fuelled by a 10 per cent rise in agricultural price, including
a 31 per cent jump in fruit and vegetable prices. In manufacturing, private
sector prices rose 5.5 per cent over August, and state industries 5.8 per
cent.
With the year-on-year inflation rate now running at 67.7 per cent, few
economists believe the government will achieve its forecast target of 45-50
per cent by the year end.
